Hi Adriene! I'm writing on behalf of my mom and I to thank you for all of your videos - we just finished 365 days of yoga practice! We started July 22, 2019 thinking it would be great if we could just get through this one 30 Days of Yoga and before we knew it we were well on our way to a whole year. In the last week and a half leading up to day 365 my mom and I were both injured, her back my foot, but because you provide such a diverse set of yoga videos we were able to continue our practice while healing. Living in different states, traveling, taking care of babies, power outages and injuries - none of it stopped us from finding a way to work in one of your amazing videos. We only do Yoga with Adriene and can't wait to see what the next year of practice holds! <3

Day 24  âœ”ï¸ Good morning friends! I hope everyone is taking the time they need to take a break from things. I often get so caught up with doing so many things at once that, until my body is physically telling me to stop by excessive sleepiness, fatigue, etc., I tend to keep going. Yesterday was one of those days. I wanted to take a quick nap before yoga, and I ended up waking up in the morning today. But I avoided beating myself up about it, and just moved on to today and did this yoga practice after my morning walk. And it was so amazing! A restorative practice after a nice long walk (the latter which I normally don't do at night) turned out to be a blessing in disguise. My muscles were more warm and accommodating in the stretches and my hips and shoulders opened up SO MUCH with pleasant snap-crackle-pops in the forward folds and windshield wipers. I think that is where we tend to keep our stress, so today my body was just like "damn dawg, you need to take some chill time." I realize no mount of Kale or Probiotics can fix a mentally fixed mindset. Lol.

I also tried to view the difficult yesterday as a coming of big change; often its said that things become really difficult right before a massive change happens--I remember the analogy of a pin on a balloon: the surface where the pin punctures the balloon becomes the most tense right before it explodes! 

I've been saying "no" to a lot of things since I started this practice, and sometimes it feels like a sacrifice to say no so much to things I enjoyed. But some reflections helps me realize that it's not really a sacrifice if I'm giving up things that didn't help me grow in the first place. Sure my weekends are a lot more boring, I go out a lot less frequently, and spend that time cooking or in front of a YouTube video, but oddly enough life is already much better. Namaste friends, and thank you again teacher ğŸ™

Hi Adriene - I rarely comment but feel like it's important for me to do so today. Background:  I'm a 65yo woman who's had MS for more than 40 yrs. Weakening my legs & disrupting my sense of balance. I've been doing yoga with you for about 3 yrs & it's made a (wonderful) world of difference for me. I have come to love my daily home yoga practice with Adriene! And I was absolutely loving TRUE until about 10 days ago - when all the high lunges, standing work & balance exercises began to really overwhelm me. But I carried on. The last 3 days, however, I've noticed my legs and feet hurting more & more off the mat while I was also feeling more unstable than usual. So today (day 28 for me), I was gonna just skip. But then I felt guilty & you were sitting so maybe it wouldn't be all legs again.... So I started it - oh no, â€œlet's start at the top of our matâ€ - and I went along, dreading the moment you'd say â€œslide your right leg backâ€ & then it happened. I did. Then the high lunge. And I said NO, NO, NO. NO!!!! And I quit, choosing instead to do one of fave YWA videos (Gentle Yummy Yoga, Day 24, 30 Days of Yoga). As always, that was delicious - and gave me renewed conviction to return to Day 28 of TRUE. So I did. But I kept my leg on the ground when you got to high lunges & then, after the twist, when you wanted to go further, I went my own way, returning to YWA stretches & twists that open & comfort my hips, rather than putting more strain on them. I did it with grace & intention, moving from the center, and refused to let my brain tell me I was â€œcheating.â€ I met up with for the deep squat & followed you thru the rest of the exercise - and am now so glad I didn't walk away when I got frustrated and mad, or even after Gentle Yummy Yoga because this taught me that it's my body and you can't possibly know what is best for me. That's my responsibility. You can only give me tools - and you,ve given me so, so many. It was lovely to find that I knew exactly hiw I could put some of them together today to bring me through & past my anger and annoyance to the place I always hope to be after my YWA. Long story, I know, but I needed to tell it to myself and to you. Thank you! Lesley
